  "generated_text": "To solve this problem, we need to calculate the total time Carla spends downloading the file, accounting for the pause and the restart.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the time taken during the first download.**\nThe total file size is 200 GB, and the normal download rate is 2 GB/minute.\n$$ \\text{Time}_1 = \\frac{\\text{Total Size}}{\\text{Rate}} = \\frac{200 \\text{ GB}}{2 \\text{ GB/min}} = 100 \\text{ minutes} $$\nSince the download is 40% complete, we calculate the time spent at the start of the second phase.\n$$ \\text{Time}_1 = 0.4 \\times 100 \\text{ min} = 40 \\text{ minutes} $$\nWait, the problem states \"40% of the way through the download\". This implies she has completed 40% of the total 200 GB.\nSo, the time elapsed at this point is $40\\%$ of the original download duration.\n$$ \\text{Time}_1 = 0.4 \\times 100 \\text{ min} = 40 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the time taken during the restart and second download.**\nAfter the restart, Windows forces a restart to install updates, which takes 20 minutes.\nThen, she restarts the download from the beginning. The rate remains 2 GB/minute.\nSince she has to restart the download from the beginning, the time taken for this second part is the full duration of the original download.\n$$ \\text{Time}_2 = 100 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the total time.**\nThe total time is the sum of the time taken for the first phase and the time taken for the second phase.\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = \\text{Time}_1 + \\text{Time}_2 $$\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = 40 \\text{ minutes} + 100 \\text{ minutes} = 140 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\nAlternatively, we can think of it as:\nThe process consists of two phases:\n1.  Download 40% of the file: $0.4 \\times 100 = 40$ minutes.\n2.  Wait 20 minutes for updates.\n3.  Download the remaining 60% of the file: $0.6 \\times 100 = 60$ minutes.\n4.  Wait 20 minutes for updates again.\n5.  Download the remaining 60% of the file: $0.6 \\times 100 = 60$ minutes.\n\n